John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools benefit from a curriculum of academic excellence, with this trend continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional results in the exams, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community initiatives.
With more than 30,000 students scattered throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to achieve the best level of service for both students and parents.
Independent schools intend to prepare their students for further education and access to universities, as well as for the career they have chosen and to take their place as global citizens.
Since this is an educational sector capable of designing and implementing a tailored school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and sought-after theme in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If we speak to a man in a language he understands, we can get into his mind.
If we speak to him in his own language, we can enter his heart."
This quote reminds us well that we cannot only rely on English when we want to create relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the results of recent exams this year, we verify that the languages are at the top of the tables, with the highest rates of use of independent schools.
A total of 68% of the students who studied foreign languages reached the maximum classification of A.
These data, collected in 74 schools under SCIS, show that 72% of students obtained the maximum rating of A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that Scottish independent schools are favoring foreign languages as vital skills that will undoubtedly serve children and young people in the future.
Languages, as an option, are now viewed in the same way as STEM themes (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and not only.
An investigation by the UK Employment and Competence Commission in 2014 concluded that, among the reasons for the difficulty of employers in filling vacancies, 17% concerned the lack of language skills.
Therefore, learning other languages is increasingly an imperative to prepare the young generation for their future careers.
With more potential employment opportunities to demand language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if you have learned a second language, you will have a tangible advantage in the future with an aptitude for life like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically place a multilingual person in front of competition.
According to a survey by YouGov of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, the French is the only language spoken by a two-digit ratio, 15%.
So investing in language teaching is important for today's children.
The domain of several languages, particularly those of developing countries, will give children better opportunities to find employment with relevance.
In Scotland, each school differs in the languages it teaches.
Some of them will focus on the most classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered the most important for the UK for the 2020 horizon, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a set of languages to choose from in independent schools, supported by specialized teaching staff in the area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a pedagogical environment that prepares children and gives them the skills necessary for success, whatever future reserves them.
It is undeniable that today, in a globalised business environment, languages continue to be of fundamental importance to the future of the country, so it is necessary to reflect it in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to make this option available with diversity and excellence for young Scottish people.
We have to do this right.
